{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598464"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:38:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:38:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15475"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15475"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0,0.8,0.07,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8166"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61527"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8166","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8166"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15475"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46980"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"108"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1758"},{"type":"tags","id":"2701"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19780"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19783"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61527"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents with fever, cough, and large volumes of foul-smelling purulent sputum. His medical history includes previous episodes of tuberculosis-related pneumonia. A chest X-ray demonstrates the characteristic \u0027tram track sign\u0027.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following conditions is most likely present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chronic bronchitis","Asthma","Bronchiectasis","Emphysema","Bronchiolitis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has \u003Cstrong\u003Ebronchiectasis\u003C/strong\u003E, characterised by permanent and abnormal dilation of bronchi. The classic triad includes chronic cough, large volumes of purulent sputum, and recurrent chest infections. The \u0027tram track sign\u0027 on chest X-ray represents thickened, dilated bronchial walls running parallel to each other.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic bronchitis\u003C/strong\u003E presents with productive cough but typically lacks the large volume of purulent sputum and radiological changes. \u003Cstrong\u003EAsthma\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by reversible airway obstruction and wheezing, without permanent structural changes. \u003Cstrong\u003EEmphysema\u003C/strong\u003E involves destruction of alveolar walls and typically presents with dyspnoea rather than productive cough. \u003Cstrong\u003EBronchiolitis\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects infants and small airways.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EPrevious tuberculosis infection is a common cause of bronchiectasis, as it can cause structural damage to the airways leading to chronic infection and inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bronchiectasis is characterised by permanent dilation of bronchi, often presenting with copious purulent sputum and showing tram track signs on chest X-ray","Previous tuberculosis infection is a common cause of bronchiectasis due to airway damage","Foul-smelling purulent sputum suggests colonisation and infection in damaged airways"],"references":["Mason, R. J., Broaddus, V. C., Martin, T. R., King, T. E., Schraufnagel, D., Murray, J. F., \u0026 Nadel, J. A. (2010). Murray and Nadel\u0027s textbook of respiratory medicine E-book: 2-volume set. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Bird K, Memon J. Bronchiectasis. [Updated 2023 May 22]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430810/","O\u0027Donnell AE. Bronchiectasis - A Clinical Review. N Engl J Med. 2022 Aug 11;387(6):533-545. doi: 10.1056/NEJMra2202819. PMID: 35947710.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46980"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15475"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46980","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/46980"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-15T18:18:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-15T18:19:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8166"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61527"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":